faqs:
  - q: "What is the 183-day rule?"
    a: "It's the most common test countries use to determine tax residency: spend more than 183 days (roughly half the year) in a country and that country generally treats you as tax-resident on worldwide income. Exact phrasing varies — some count consecutive days, others a calendar year, others a rolling 12-month window."
  - q: "Is the 183-day rule the only test that matters?"
    a: "No. Tax home, permanent home, center of vital interests, and habitual abode can all override or supplement the day count. Spending under 183 days doesn't automatically protect you if your tax home and family ties are still abroad. The companion guide on the 183-day rule walks through each test."
  - q: "Does this tool give me a legal conclusion?"
    a: "No. It's a screening tool. It flags situations where your inputs suggest higher residency risk and recommends professional review. It is not a substitute for a cross-border tax professional, especially when stakes are high."
  - q: "Does leaving my home country end my tax obligation there?"
    a: "Depends on the country. The US taxes citizens on worldwide income regardless of where they live. Most other countries operate on residency-based taxation, where properly established non-residency ends the obligation — but 'properly' has specific requirements. Both sides need answers."
  - q: "When should I talk to a cross-border tax pro instead of using a calculator?"
    a: "If you're splitting time across multiple countries, maintaining significant home-country ties, planning a multi-year move, living in a country with aggressive residency tests, or having unusual income (capital gains, equity events, business sale) during the move year. The calculator flags these; a professional handles them."
